sect2:
Booting with TFTP
&boot-installer-intro-net.xml;
On machines with OpenBoot, simply enter the boot monitor on the machine which is being installed (see ). Use the command boot net to boot from a TFTP and RARP server, or try boot net:bootp or boot net:dhcp to boot from a TFTP and BOOTP or DHCP server. Some older OpenBoot revisions require using the device name, such as boot le(); these probably don't support BOOTP nor DHCP.

Booting from a CD-ROM
&boot-installer-intro-cd.xml;
Most OpenBoot versions support the boot cdrom command which is simply an alias to boot from the SCSI device on ID 6 (or the secondary master for IDE based systems). You may have to use the actual device name for older OpenBoot versions that don't support this special command. Note that some problems have been reported on Sun4m (e.g., Sparc 10s and Sparc 20s) systems booting from CD-ROM.
